Regression, Variable Selection, and Partial Least Squares

This lab uses a case study in chemistry to highlight key concepts in regression modeling. There are several questions embedded throughout the lab that will assume knowledge of the caret package, principle components analysis (PCA), and multiple linear regression. The lab will build knowledge and intution in data exploration and pre-processing, variable selection, principle components regression, partial least squares regression, and LASSO regression.

Case Study - Drug Solubility

Chemical compounds, such as drugs, can be represented through chemical formulas describing their atomic components. For example, the popular drug aspirin contains nine carbon, eight hydrogen, and four oxygen atoms held together by various different chemical bonds. Using the chemical configuration, certain additional measures, such as molecular weight, surface area, or polarity, can be derived. However, there are many useful attributes that cannot be derived analytically, and their measurement typically requires careful labratory experiments.

One such attribute (that cannot be determined analytically) is a compound’s solubility, or how it behaves in a liquid solution. Solubility is important because it determines whether a drug can be given orally or needs to be administered via injection. The case study in this lab will explore modeling the solubility of chemical compounds using analytically derived variables.

Our case study is based upon research done by Teko et al. (2001) and Huuskonen (2000), and borrows from the text Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson. The goal is to model the solubility of a compound using descriptors of its chemical structure. The idea is to use the model to screen compounds, some of which might not yet exist, for diserable properties. In general, this type of study investigates the quantitative structure-activity relationship (QSAR), and QSAR modeling is becoming increasingly prevalent in many areas of chemistry.

Data Exploration and Pre-processing

The first step in most modeling building applications is to reserve a portion of the data for the test set. Recall that we use the test set only at the very end of the model building process, it allows us to get an unbiased assessment of how successful the model will be on new data. This is necessary because everything we do (ranging from data visualization to variable selection to model choice) using the training data induces the possibility of overfitting.

library(caret)
#install.packages("AppliedPredictiveModeling")
library(AppliedPredictiveModeling)

data(solubility)
X <- rbind(solTestX, solTrainX)
y <- c(solTestY, solTrainY)
data <- data.frame(Solubility = y, X)

set.seed(1234)
test.id <- sample(1:nrow(X), size = .2*nrow(X)) ## Randomly choose 20% of rows for test set

test.data <- data[test.id,]  ## Subset to include rows designated to test set
train.data <- data[-test.id,]  ## Exclude rows designated to test set

After partitioning the data we can use the training data to begin to understand the predictor variables and how they relate with the outcome variable “Solubility”.

head(train.data)

These data contain: - 208 binary variables that indicate the presence/absence of a specific chemical substructure - 16 count variables that indicate number of bonds or atoms of a specific type - 4 continuous variables indicating analytically derived characteristics like molecular weight or surface area - The outcome, solubility, which is measured on the log-scale

Because the overall number of predictors is moderate-to-high, we should be interested in variable selection, and/or dimension reduction. The first thing we should do is check for highly correlated predictors. Correlation is questionably defined for binary variables, so we will focus on the 20 count/continuous variables:

## Only show the 20 analytic vars
#install.packages("corrplot")
library(corrplot)  ## A library for visualizing correlations
cor.matrix <- cor(train.data[,210:ncol(train.data)])  ## Find pairwise correlation matrix
corrplot(cor.matrix, type = "upper", method = "square") ## Plot the corr matrix

Continuing our analysis, we’ll use 8 variables derived from PCA as a lower dimensional representation of the original 20 variables. The scores for each component for each observation are stored in x within the object created by prcomp:

P <- prcomp(train.data[,210:ncol(train.data)], scale = TRUE)
#head(P$x)

For clarity, we’ll setup a new training data object using only these 8 derived variables (and the outcome variable Solubility):

train.data2 <- data.frame(Solubility = train.data$Solubility, P$x[,1:8])

Relationships with the outcome

PCA (by design) ignores the outcome variable; consequently, there is no garauntee that each (or any) component is predictive of solubility. We should explore this graphically:

library(tidyr)
## Tidy these data for plotting with ggplot
plot.df <- gather(train.data2, key = "Component", value = "X", 2:9)

ggplot(plot.df, aes(x = X, y = Solubility)) + geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, span = 2) +  ## span alters the smoothness
  facet_wrap( ~ Component, scales = "free")

Interpretting this plot, we see that some of the components appear to be associated with solubility, while others don’t seem to be very predictive. We also see that fourth component might have a non-linear relationship with solubility. Typically, real non-linear relationships occur for an identifiable reason, so we should try to interpret this component:

fviz_contrib(P, choice = "var", axes = 4)

P$rotation[,4]
##         MolWeight          NumAtoms      NumNonHAtoms          NumBonds 
##      0.2584510545      0.0315405601      0.0623818844      0.0146473635 
##      NumNonHBonds      NumMultBonds       NumRotBonds       NumDblBonds 
##      0.0266645116     -0.3458979451      0.1256610469      0.1420161837 
##  NumAromaticBonds       NumHydrogen         NumCarbon       NumNitrogen 
##     -0.3703608707     -0.0002358333     -0.0729175467     -0.2157567694 
##         NumOxygen         NumSulfer       NumChlorine        NumHalogen 
##      0.1394703466      0.0019996931      0.5127105621      0.5229855536 
##          NumRings HydrophilicFactor      SurfaceArea1      SurfaceArea2 
##     -0.1569204616      0.0404384449      0.0135100957      0.0216224609

A compound will have high score in this component if it has a lot of halogen/cholrine atoms, but not many “Mult” or “Aromatic” bonds. Similarly, it will have a low score in this component if it has few halogen/cholrine atoms and a lot of “Mult” or “Aromatic” bonds. Both high and low scores seem to correspond with low solubility.

If you were actually working on this model you might want to consult with a chemist regarding this interpretation, since it implies a quadratic effect should be used when including this component in the model. All of the other component’s relationships with solubility appear to be roughly linear (we shouldn’t worry too much about the points near the edges of each plot that are clearly curving loess trendline)

Model Building

An advantage of using caret for model building is the common formula syntax that is compatible with many types of models. In this syntax, the outcome variable is specified first and is seperated from predictor variables by the ~ character. Next predictor variables (or functions of them!) are specified, separated by + characters.

## We will evaluate models using repeated cross validation
fit.control = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats = 10)


## Find original vars most correlated with solubility

Question 3: Based upon the results above which model is superior, the linear regression model that uses the two variables which were most correlated with Solubility, or the linear regression model that uses the first two principle components?

Neither of these models is likely to be optimal, the general workflow we should use is to add a predictor/group of predictors (or modify the form of an existing predictor), then use caret to determine if the change improves out-of-sample prediction error. The idea is to slowly increase the complexity of the model until we strike an ideal balance between performance and interpretability for our goals.

## Some additional models:
model3 <- formula(Solubility ~ PC1 + PC2 + PC3)
model4 <- formula(Solubility ~ PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4)
## The poly function can be used to add non-linear effects
model4q <- formula(Solubility ~ PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + poly(PC4, degree = 2))


set.seed(15)
fit.lm3 <- train(model3, data = train.data2, method = "lm", trControl = fit.control)
set.seed(15)
fit.lm4 <- train(model4, data = train.data2, method = "lm", trControl = fit.control)
set.seed(15)
fit.lm4q <- train(model4q, data = train.data2, method = "lm", trControl = fit.control)

## Compare these new models
resamps <- resamples(list(lm2 = fit.lm2, lm3 = fit.lm3, lm4 = fit.lm4, lm4q = fit.lm4q))
resamps2 <- gather(resamps$values, key = "Var", value = "Val", 2:ncol(resamps$values))
resamps2 <- separate(resamps2, col = "Var", into = c("Model", "Metric"), sep = "~")

ggplot(resamps2, aes(x = Model, y = Val)) + geom_boxplot() + facet_wrap(~ Metric, scales = "free")

We also might consider applying these variable selection algorithms to the orignal variables (rather than the derived principle components); however, this causes some problems:

## This produces many warning messages!
backward_subs_original <- rfe(train.data[,210:ncol(train.data)], train.data$Solubility, rfeControl = ctrl, seed = 15)

Several of the original variables are linear combinations of the others. Principle components naturally accomodates this, but for regression it is problematic and results in untrustworthy models. We can use the FindLinearCombos function in the caret package to help us out:

lin.coms <- findLinearCombos(train.data[,210:ncol(train.data)])
lin.coms$linearCombos
## [[1]]
## [1] 5 2 3 4
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 10  2  3

Very clearly, variables 2 through 5 are not linearly independent, which makes sense given that the total number of atoms is a function of the number of nitrogen, carbon, etc. We should remove variables so that all columns of the data matrix are linearly independent. By further inspecting the variables, it seems like “NumBonds”, “NumNonHBonds”, “NumAtoms”, and “NumNonHAtoms” are likely to be functions of other variables and should be removed:

to.remove <- which(names(train.data[,210:ncol(train.data)]) %in% c("NumAtoms", "NumBonds", "NumNonHAtoms", "NumNonHBonds"))
new.train.X <- train.data[,210:ncol(train.data)]
new.train.X <- new.train.X[,-to.remove]
findLinearCombos(new.train.X)  ## Check if any linear combos remain
## $linearCombos
## list()

## $remove
## NULL

Partial Least Squares (PLS)

Notice how the cross-validated RMSE is substantially lower for many models than it was when we did principle components regression. This is not necessarily unusual, principle components analysis is an unsupervised learning approach, so it is effective in dimension reduction, but there is no garauntee that any of the new dimensions will be associated with the response.

PCA blindly chases variability with no consideration of the outcome variable, so you might expect that a more targeted approach which considers the outcome variability will be more effective for supervised learning problems. One such method is Partial Least Squares (PLS).

PLS is similar to PCA in the sense that it constructs new derived dimensions in \(X\), but it operates such that covariance between \(X\) and \(Y\) is maximized for each newly derived dimension. Thus, the first component of PLS is a linear combination of the original variables that is most strongly related with \(Y\).

set.seed(15)
pls.fit <- train(Solubility ~ .,  data = train.data[,c(1,210:ncol(train.data))], method = "pls", trControl = fit.control, tuneGrid = data.frame(ncomp = 1:20))
pls.fit

Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator (LASSO)

So far we’ve neglected the 208 binary structure variables, which could potentially improve our predictions. There are too many of these variables to expect good results from foward/backward variable selection, and PCA/PLS aren’t designed for binary variables (though there is some debate on whether they could be applied). An efficient and powerful a alternative method, the LASSO, is well-suited for this situation.

While the LASSO is implemented in caret, the ncvreg package itself offers a better implementation of cross validation:

library(ncvreg)
set.seed(15)
cv.fit <- cv.ncvreg(X = train.data[,-1], y = train.data$Solubility, penalty = "lasso")
summary(cv.fit)
## lasso-penalized linear regression with n=1014, p=228
## At minimum cross-validation error (lambda=0.0069):
## -------------------------------------------------
##   Nonzero coefficients: 133
##   Cross-validation error (deviance): 0.47
##   R-squared: 0.89
##   Signal-to-noise ratio: 8.03
##   Scale estimate (sigma): 0.687
plot(cv.fit)

We can see that the cross-validated \(R^2\) goes up by about 10% using this model (which incorperates the 208 binary structure features). The cross-validation error reported by ncvreg is not square-rooted, so for this LASSO model \(RMSE = \sqrt{0.47} = 0.686\).

In any LASSO model only a subset of the available predictors are active (make a non-zero contribution to the model). We can see the set of selected features (and their regression coefficients) using the commands below:

## Within cv.fit is the fitted lasso model (fit)
## Within the fitted model is beta, a matrix of regression coefficients for each lambda
## We want only the column of beta corresponding to the lambda that minimizes CV RSME
all_coefs <- cv.fit$fit$beta[,cv.fit$fit$lambda == cv.fit$lambda.min]
all_coefs[all_coefs != 0]

Question 8: Use forward feature selection (implemented in the ffs function, see the slides for an example) on the data (including the 208 binary structure features) using method = "lm". How does this model compare to the LASSO model? (compare their predictive performance and selected variables)

Conclusions

In this application we saw that using a reduced set of derived dimensions offered an advantage over using subsets of the original variables, but only if the construction of those dimensions took the outcome variable into consideration (partial least squares performed better than principle components regression). We then saw that the 208 binary features could aid prediction even further the appropriate method was used to perform feature selection.
